canonical:
  title: 希賢堂銘
  author: 李永瑞
  language: lzh
  text: 天降斯民均賦是理曰賢曰愚初無少異道本在邇士貴尙志希之則是吾何畏彼希之如何誠之而已謂力不足是自畫爾謂若登天是爲自棄九仞之高一簣焉始其止其往皆在我爾俛焉思齊日惟仰止志不違仁事顔之事身任天下恥尹之恥擧獲之任是亦獲矣勖哉夫子永言顧諟
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 希賢堂銘
  author: 李永瑞
  language: lzh
  text: 天降斯民。均賦是理。曰賢曰愚。初無少異。道本在邇。士貴尙志。希之則是。吾何畏彼。希之如何。誠之而已。謂力不足。是自畫爾。謂若登天。是爲自棄。九仞之高。一簣焉始。其止其往。皆在我爾。俛焉思齊。日惟仰止。志不違仁。事顔之事。身任天下。恥尹之恥。擧獲之任。是亦獲矣。勖哉夫子。永言顧諟。
korean:
  title: 희현당 명
  author: 이영서
  language: kor
  text: |-
    하늘이 내리신 이 백성
    한결같이 그 이치 받았나니
    어리석고 어질다 묻지 마소
    애초부터 조금도 다름 없네
    도는 본시 가까운 데 있고
    선비는 뜻을 높이 가져야지
    바람대로 되는 것이거늘
    내 어찌 그들을 두려워하리
    바라기를 어떻게 하랴
    성으로 할 따름인저
    힘이 모자란다 이른다면
    스스로 한계를 긋는 것
    하늘에 오르기와 같다 하면
    스스로 포기하는 것이라네
    구인의 높이도
    한 삼태기 흙으로 비롯되나니
    그치느냐 나가느냐
    모두가 스스로에 있는 것
    머리 숙이고 부지런히 하여
    날로 오직 우러르며
    인을 어기지 않기로 뜻을 가져
    안자의 하던 일을 일삼고
    몸바쳐 천하를 책임하여
    이윤의 부끄럼과 같이 하소
    오확의 짐을 들면
    그 역시 오확이니
    부자여 노력하여
    길이 이 말을 생각하시라
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_0530_010_0180&viewSync=OT
english:
  title: Inscription for the Hall of Aspiring to Worthiness
  author: Lee Young-seo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Heaven bestows this people equally,
    All sharing in the same underlying principle.
    Do not distinguish the foolish from the wise—
    From the start, there is no difference between them.

    The Way lies near at hand;
    A scholar's worth lies in the height of his ambition.
    If you aspire to it, it becomes yours—
    Why then should I fear others?

    How should one aspire?
    Through sincerity alone.

    If you say your strength is insufficient,
    You only draw limits upon yourself.
    If you claim it is like climbing heaven,
    You abandon yourself entirely.

    Even a tower nine fathoms high
    Begins with a single basket of earth.
    Whether you halt or advance,
    All depends on yourself alone.

    Bow your head and labor diligently,
    Each day looking ever upward.
    Let your will not deviate from benevolence,
    Making the pursuits of Yan Hui your own.
    Claim the burden of all under heaven,
    Sharing the shame of Yi Yin.

    Take up the task of Wu Huo—
    It too becomes yours.

    O worthy one, exert yourself,
    And ponder these words forever.
  footnotes:
    - Yan Hui (顏回) was Confucius's most devoted disciple, known for his singular dedication to virtue and learning.
    - Yi Yin (伊尹) was a legendary minister who felt shame at any failing in the empire, embodying perfect moral responsibility.
    - Wu Huo (烏獲) was a legendary figure known for extraordinary strength; the reference suggests that great tasks become manageable through sincere effort and determination.
